The registry has the v4.19 catalog image, but that alone does not guarantee newer RHODF supporting bundles are present inside the catalog currently used by OLM.

Right now your subscriptions still resolve to:

4.18.17-rhodf

and OLM says:

AtLatestKnown

So either:

Red Hat intentionally kept those component versions at 4.18.17 for RHODF 4.19

OR your catalog pod is still using older cached index data


You can verify what bundle versions are actually visible to OLM.

Check available channels:

oc get packagemanifest rook-ceph-operator -o jsonpath='{.status.channels[*].currentCSV}'

and:

oc get packagemanifest ocs-operator -o jsonpath='{.status.channels[*].currentCSV}'

Also:

oc get packagemanifest mcg-operator -o jsonpath='{.status.channels[*].currentCSV}'

If they still show:

4.18.17-rhodf


then your catalog itself does not expose newer component CSVs.

In that case, this is expected/supported RHODF packaging behavior and there is nothing to upgrade.

If you do see newer 4.19.x-rhodf CSVs available but subscriptions are stuck, then refresh marketplace cache:

oc delete pod -n openshift-marketplace --all

Wait a few minutes and recheck:

oc get installplan -A
oc get csv -A

But based on all the outputs so far, this looks like an intentional RHODF component version mapping rather than a failed upgrade.
